+| `infrastructure-server-subresources` | GET, PATCH, POST | `~/v1/regions/{region}/infrastructure/servers/[^/]+/providerSpecificData$`, `~/v1/regions/{region}/infrastructure/servers/[^/]+/cloudConfig$`, `~/v1/regions/{region}/infrastructure/servers/[^/]+$` (three anchored regexes) | infrastructure | regional `svc-<region>-workflow-worker`; default `svc-local-workflow-worker` | KCS-678: the `ProvisionReservations` child workflow (`services/workflow/cmd/workflow-worker/workflows/child-workflows/management-apis/infrastructure/provision_reservation.go`), invoked today only by `instance-group-create` (KCS-932, `provision-hosts` step — `cluster-deployment-create-v3` only *reads* server PSD off the reservation, it doesn't patch it), hits three server-scoped endpoints after the reservation lands: `PATCH /servers/{slug}/providerSpecificData` (write NIC interfaces from the rendered NetworkConfig), `POST /servers/{slug}/cloudConfig` (write the node-specific cloud-config), and `GET /servers/{slug}` (poll `provisioned` in `GetServerProvisionState`). All three are dual-auth in the Go handler (`services/infrastructure/cmd/infrastructure/routes.go:210-221`; endpoints landed in KCS-678 / #565) but their internal-listener companion was never added — worker calls fell through to the external `infrastructure` route (path prefix `~/.../servers`, above) and were 403'd by `k0rdent-authz` in `listener_mode=external` (the `client_credentials` service JWT carries no `k0r` user claim; `K0rdentClaimEnricher.java:190-194` deliberately skips `svc-*` clients). Unlike `infrastructure-reservations` above, external RBAC access to these same three paths is a live use case (operators inspecting server state and NIC config), so this route can't just shadow the external `infrastructure` route the way reservations do — one Kong route with binary `listener_mode` can't serve both audiences. Instead this route ships an **`internalHosts` Host filter** (`kong-internal`, `kong-internal.<ns>`, `kong-internal.<ns>.svc.cluster.local`) and runs ALONGSIDE the external `infrastructure` route: the internal route only matches requests to `Host: kong-internal(:8100)` — which is how every internal caller in the repo reaches Kong (`deploy/helm/charts/services/*/values.yaml` `WORKFLOW_API_ENDPOINT` / `INTERNAL_API_BASE_URL`, all `http://kong-internal:8100`) — and external users hit a different Host and fall through to the external route. Kong ranks routes with a `hosts` filter above equivalent routes without one when the Host matches, so both audiences land on the right route deterministically without a `regex_priority` tiebreaker. Defense-in-depth: `listener_mode=internal` + `internal_listener_port` stays in front; a spoofed `Host: kong-internal` on the external port still 403s with "wrong listener". This is the row the `svc-*-workflow-worker` kind in `INFRA_INTERNAL_ALLOWED_SERVICE_IDS` mirrors (alongside `infrastructure-reservations`). No other caller is planned. |
