 | `workflow-workflows` | POST, GET | `/v1/workflow/workflows/{templateRef}`, `…/executions/{executionId}`, `…/executions/{executionId}/cancel`, `…/executions/{executionId}/retry`, `…/executions/{executionId}/signals/{signalName}` | workflow | in-cluster: regional `svc-<region>-{compute,infrastructure}` (default `svc-local-*`) + regional `svc-<region>-workflow-worker` (default `svc-local-workflow-worker`, KCS-68) + central `svc-organizations`; cross-cluster (regional render only): `svc-global-workflow-worker` | Compute / infrastructure / organizations kick off async work via `internal/workflow/workflow_client.go`. Pre-KCS-173 these calls hit the external listener with `X-API-Key`; KCS-173 moves them to the internal listener with `client_credentials` JWTs. Mixed caller class is intentional: compute and infrastructure are regional (region-scoped `svc-<region>-<service>` clients, minted per the KCS-1099 configured-secret derivation), organizations is central. **KCS-798**: on the **regional** render the route is marked `crossCluster` and its `allowedCallers` are replaced with the regional compute/infrastructure callers + the **global** workflow-worker (`svc-global-workflow-worker`) — the global `OrgDelete` worker dispatches the regional `org-resource-teardown` workflow across clusters via the regional gateway NodePort (KCS-68). crossCluster omits the internal-listener port check; `allowedCallers` + JWT/JWKS stays the gate. `svc-organizations` dispatches org-lifecycle workflows to the workflow service **in-cluster** (workflow runs on the global cluster too), never cross-cluster. |
